          "body": "The chapter's closing image is among the most ironic in the Former Prophets. Adonijah, who had prepared chariots and horsemen and fifty men to run before him (1:5), ends the day clinging to the horns of the altar in fear (1:50). The altar is the place of sacrifice and mercy, not of political power. His flight there invokes the Mosaic provision of Exodus 21:12-14 — a place of asylum — but that provision was for the unintentional killer, not the would-be usurper. Solomon's response (1:52-53) is calibrated: conditional mercy, not amnesty. 'If he is a worthy man, not one of his hairs will fall to the ground; but if wickedness is found in him, he will die.' The new king's first act is both merciful and ominous — Adonijah goes home under a sword he cannot see. The narrator expects readers of 2:19-25 to remember this conditional carefully."
