        "excerpt": "Now Adonijah the son of Haggith exalted himself, saying, 'I will be king.'",
        "body": "The opening four verses are a deliberate portrait of diminishment. David cannot keep warm (1:1); his servants must search the territory for a caretaker (1:2-3); the girl is very beautiful and the king does not cohabit with her (1:4) — a detail that signals not merely abstinence but the near-total absence of royal vitality. The narrator is showing a vacancy. Swindoll (Great Lives: David) notes that this is the David of the Psalms reduced to his final chapter — the warrior who killed Goliath now unable to regulate his body temperature. The detail is pastoral as well as narrative: human greatness does not exempt from physical finitude.\n\nAdonijah reads the vacancy with political precision. He is the fourth son of David (2 Samuel 3:4), the eldest surviving after Amnon (murdered, 2 Samuel 13) and Absalom (killed in rebellion, 2 Samuel 18). By ancient Near Eastern primogeniture logic, he has a case. His preparation — chariots, horsemen, fifty runners (1:5) — mirrors Absalom's identical political theater (2 Samuel 15:1), and the narrator intends the parallel. Adonijah is Absalom's shadow, repeating the pattern of a son who cannot wait for God's timing.\n\nThe narrator's theological verdict falls in verse 6: 'His father had never crossed him at any time by asking, \"Why have you done so?\"' This is not a minor character note. The Hebrew for 'crossed' (*atsav*, to grieve, to pain) suggests David's failure was not ignorance but emotional avoidance — he would not bear the pain of confrontation. Eli's failure at Shiloh (1 Samuel 2:22-25) casts its shadow here. Unchastened sons who are handsome and bold do not self-correct; they escalate. The coalition Adonijah assembles — Joab and Abiathar (1:7) — is experienced and capable, but the narrator's 'but' in verse 8 is devastating: Zadok, Nathan, Benaiah, and the mighty men of David are not with him. The men who carry the covenant's momentum are absent from the pretender's table.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nasa naphsho* (1:5) — 'exalted himself' is literally 'lifted his soul' — the idiom for presumptuous self-elevation (cf. Psalm 24:4; Ezekiel 17:14). *Kohen* (priest) appears twice in vv. 7-8, once for Abiathar (with Adonijah) and once for Zadok (against him) — the split priesthood is highlighted by the repeated noun in contrasting contexts."
